03":"1603","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom",", Nottingham, England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lockard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Lockhart   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Lockhart","meanings":["Scottish and English: nickname from Old French <i>locart</i>, a Normanno-Picard form of Old French <i>lo(s)chart</i> ‘one who squints, who is cross-eyed’, attested in 13th- and 14th-century Arras (Pas-de-Calais) as <i>Louchard</i>, <i>Lochard</i>, <i>Locard</i> and <i>Locart</i>. It is a derivative of Latin <i>luscus</i> ‘one-eyed’. In France <b>Locard</b> is mostly found in Normandy (especially Calvados) <i>c.</i> 1900, while <b>Louchart</b> is mainly concentrated in Pas-de-Calais at the same time.","Americanized form of German   Luckhardt  .","History: According to family tradition, Sir Simon Locard held the key to the locked silver casket in which Robert the Bruce's heart was taken to be buried in the Holy Land in 1329. This unverifiable story is no doubt related to the later spelling of the Scottish surname as <i>Lockhart</i> and to the addition of a heart and fetterlock to the family coat of arms (date unknown)."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sarah Lockard was born in 1525, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Lockard, was 20 and her mother, Lockard, was 20. She married Eugene Travis in 1544, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1525–":"1525–Surnud","1525–Female":"1525–Surnud","1520–1603":"1520–1603","1545–1609":"1545–1609","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1525":"1525","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1520":"1520","1609":"1609","1505":"1505","1603":"1603","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", Nottingham, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1525–":"1525–Kuollut","1525–Female":"1525–Kuollut","1520–1603":"1520–1603","1545–1609":"1545–1609","1505–Male":"1505–Kuollut","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1525":"1525","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1520":"1520","1609":"1609","1505":"1505","1603":"1603","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",", Nottingham, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1525–":"1525–Décédée","1525–Female":"1525–Décédée","1520–1603":"1520–1603","1545–1609":"1545–1609","1505–Male":"1505–Décédé","1505–Female":"1505–Décédée","1525":"1525","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","1520":"1520","1609":"1609","1505":"1505","1603":"1603","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni",", Nottingham, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sarah Lockard est née en 1525, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Lockard, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Lockard, avait 20 ans. Elle a épousé Eugene Travis en 1544, à Nottinghamshi